Visit https://t.co/iG91xHhQN4 for a detailed look at our Smart Restart plan as we gear up to safely resume classes and campus operations this fall.

We're all in this together, Badgers ❤️ #OnWisconsin

Today’s announcement is just the beginning. Reopening is a complex process that requires changes to virtually every aspect of our operations. We will share additional information with students, faculty and staff throughout the summer.

While many classes will be offered in person, we will use virtual instruction as well, including for students who are not able to be on campus. This hybrid approach allows us to be flexible and provide ample protection to our students, faculty and staff.

We plan to begin fall classes as scheduled on Sept 2 and offer in-person instruction in many courses until the Thanksgiving recess. After Thanksgiving, we’ll switch to a virtual format for all courses for the final nine days of instruction plus exams.

Our top priorities are keeping our community healthy and continuing to provide a world-class educational experience. We are following public health guidance and will use protective measures such as face covering, physical distancing, cleaning and regular testing.

Badgers, we're planning for a Smart Restart of in-person classes this fall, beginning Sept 2.

Your wellbeing is our top priority. We're planning all the necessary steps for safety, including testing, face coverings & physical distancing.

“Keep, ancient lands, your storied pomp!” cries she
With silent lips. “Give me your tired, your poor,
Your huddled masses yearning to breathe free,
The wretched refuse of your teeming shore.
Send these, the homeless, tempest-tost to me,
I lift my lamp beside the golden door!”

A mighty woman with a torch, whose flame
Is the imprisoned lightning, and her name
Mother of Exiles. From her beacon-hand
Glows world-wide welcome; her mild eyes command
The air-bridged harbor that twin cities frame.

Not like the brazen giant of Greek fame,
With conquering limbs astride from land to land;
Here at our sea-washed, sunset gates shall stand

So even with the stress and anxiety and unprecedented challenges that we are facing with this pandemic, we can be grateful for the many opportunities to recognize our basic good nature and to extend our self-care to the caring for so many others. #COVID19
When we train our lens of awareness on these acts of kindness, we can’t help but be moved by the basic goodness that lies at the core of our actions.

Tip 4: Take this as an opportunity to appreciate the contributions of those around us for all they’re doing to help in this crisis; whether it’s practicing #socialdistancing, serving on the front lines of testing & treatment or delivering supplies to those in most critical need.

Tip 3: If you are feeling frustrated or a bit claustrophobic about remaining at home so much of the time, try to remind yourself that the plight of many others is just as, and in some cases, much more challenging.

Tip 2: Become aware of how extraordinarily interconnected we are. Both the spread of the #coronavirus itself and the choices we make to decrease the likelihood of its spreading underscore our deeply intertwined nature.

Tip 1: The next time you make the choice to take a meeting by video or to stay home, take a moment to reflect on this as a compassionate act, reflecting on how this decision to practice #socialdistancing is at its core for the benefit of others.
So what can we do beyond #socialdistancing and personal hygiene that our health professionals are recommending?
For staying physically safe, we strongly recommend following updates from the @CDCgov in the U.S. and the @WHO outside of the U.S.

This pandemic also starkly reminds us of our interdependence and how connected we are to one another. The spread of the #coronavirus does not honor national boundaries, religions, socioeconomic status, or racial and ethnic differences.
Let that sink in – the primary motivation for #socialdistancing is to benefit others. #COVID19 #StayHomeSaveLives

In addition to minimizing the likelihood of exposure ourselves, #socialdistancing is also an act of generosity and compassion toward others by eliminating our interactions as a possible vector for viral transmission.

We are living in a situation many have never seen before with #COVID19 (#coronavirus). There is pervasive anxiety and uncertainty. We have all been placed in a unique position to contemplate our motivations/intentions that guide our behavior.

Our basic goodness shines as we take on the challenges of #COVID19. 

@UWMadison professor Richard Davidson, founder of @healthyminds, reflects on how #socialdistancing is an act of generosity and compassion toward others. https://t.co/DNVNmyEyRf

Thank you to everyone for their patience and creativity as we deal with these changes over the next month. We’ll continue to adapt our plans as information changes, keeping the health and safety of our campus community at the center of our decisions to update campus.

While students may not feel like COVID-19 will affect them if they are young or healthy, please remember that you are members of a larger community and could carry it to those with compromised immune systems or to older or higher-risk people.
Viruses do not discriminate. We need everyone’s support during this challenging time and to treat each other with respect and kindness.

COVID-19 is not specific to an ethnicity or race. Racist behaviors or stereotyping in or outside of the classroom are not tolerated at UW–Madison. We encourage students who experienced harassment or discrimination to file a bias incident report: https://t.co/HgZ7QbDrLQ

Employees should not report to work if they are ill and should use sick leave or contact their supervisor or HR rep. Faculty and instructional staff are advised to continue to show flexibility to students around academic assignments, exams or other requirements.

If you develop symptoms, stay at home — please do not come to work or class if you are ill. If symptoms like fever, cough, or difficulty breathing are present, you are advised to contact your health care provider for advice. https://t.co/p1D0QG8ZMR

All campus events (including @UWMadisonExt-sponsored events outside of Dane County) of more than 50 people are canceled through at least April 10, with limited exceptions to be granted by deans or vice chancellors.

Be aware that if you travel, you may be required to self-isolate for 14 days depending on where you’re traveling to and from, even if you do not exhibit symptoms. View a list of areas that require a self-quarantine here: https://t.co/JbPzqXhUzL
We strongly advise you to reconsider non-essential personal travel, including travel over spring break. Documented cases are growing rapidly both domestically and internationally.

All university-sponsored travel is cancelled through April 10. Those who travel regularly as part of their job will typically continue to do so, but should check with their deans or other unit directors.

Campus will remain open and all faculty and staff should continue their regular work schedules unless advised otherwise by their dean, director or supervisor. Faculty and instructional staff will receive info from the Provost’s Office about the transition to online instruction.
We expect that most off-campus residents will remain in Madison and continue their studies remotely, although some may choose to remain in their permanent location past the end of spring break.
Students who stay in residence halls should be prepared for a reduced campus experience with limited opportunities for interaction and reduced campus services.

We recognize that some students may be unable to return to their permanent residence for various reasons and will need to stay in their residence halls. @HousingUW will provide additional guidance to students. Res halls will remain available to these students where necessary.

We’re particularly concerned about the safety of students in our residence halls. Residents are being asked to take essential belongings and academic materials with them for spring break and not return to residence halls following spring break through at least April 10.

Following spring break, online delivery of classes will begin on March 23 and continue at least through Friday, April 10. A decision on when and whether in-person instruction will resume will be shared in early April.
@mbgoins Face-to-face instruction will suspend March 14, or the start of spring break. Online course delivery will begin on Monday, March 23.

As COVID-19 continues to spread, the health of the UW–Madison community is our most important priority.

UW–Madison will suspend Spring Semester face-to-face instruction effective Monday, March 23.
